NUI (Native UI) is how you render HTML, CSS, and JavaScript on top of the GTA V game world. Every custom HUD, inventory screen, phone UI, and menu in FiveM runs through NUI. This lesson builds a functional NUI overlay from scratch — the foundation for every interface you will ever build.

### What this lesson covers
- You'll build: A FiveM resource that shows an HTML overlay with a button, sends data between Lua and JavaScript, and closes cleanly.
- Time: ~25 minutes
- You need: A local FiveM server, basic knowledge of HTML and JavaScript.
- You'll learn: Setting up NUI in fxmanifest, sending messages with SendNUIMessage, receiving with RegisterNUICallback, and focusing input correctly with SetNuiFocus.

### Before you start
- I can create a FiveM resource with client.lua and fxmanifest.lua.
- I know basic HTML (div, button, input) and JavaScript (addEventListener, fetch).
- I have read the Two Worlds lesson (client vs server).

> **NUI runs in a browser**
> NUI is a Chromium Embedded Framework (CEF) browser instance rendered on top of the game. Your HTML/CSS/JS runs exactly like a web page — `console.log` goes to the F8 console, and `fetch` can call external APIs (with CSP configured).

## Build it

### Step 1 - Create the resource skeleton
_Goal: The folder structure and manifest are ready._

```text
resources/qu_nui_demo/
  fxmanifest.lua
  client.lua
  html/
    index.html
    style.css
    script.js
```

```lua fxmanifest.lua
fx_version 'cerulean'
game 'gta5'

client_script 'client.lua'

ui_page 'html/index.html'

files {
    'html/index.html',
    'html/style.css',
    'html/script.js',
}
```

`ui_page` tells FiveM which HTML file to load. `files {}` lists every file NUI needs so the client downloads them.

### Step 2 - Build the HTML page
_Goal: A basic overlay with a button and a text display._

```html html/index.html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
    <div id="app">
        <h1>NUI Demo</h1>
        <p id="message">Waiting for game data...</p>
        <button id="closeBtn">Close</button>
    </div>
    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

```css html/style.css
body {
    margin: 0;
    font-family: system-ui, sans-serif;
    color: white;
}
#app {
    position: absolute;
    top: 50%;
    left: 50%;
    transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
    background: rgba(0,0,0,0.85);
    padding: 32px;
    border-radius: 8px;
    text-align: center;
}
button {
    padding: 10px 24px;
    background: #0fb6c4;
    border: none;
    color: black;
    font-weight: bold;
    cursor: pointer;
    border-radius: 4px;
    margin-top: 12px;
}
```

### Step 3 - Open NUI from Lua
_Goal: Pressing a key opens the overlay._

```lua client.lua
-- Open NUI when player presses F2
Citizen.CreateThread(function()
    while true do
        if IsControlJustPressed(0, 38) then  -- 38 = E key
            SetNuiFocus(true, true)  -- keyboard focus + cursor
            SendNUIMessage({
                type = 'open',
                message = 'Hello from Lua!'
            })
        end
        Citizen.Wait(0)
    end
end)
```

`SetNuiFocus(true, true)` — first arg = keyboard input, second arg = mouse cursor. Both `true` so the player can type and click inside NUI.

### Step 4 - Receive messages in JavaScript
_Goal: The overlay shows data sent from Lua._

```javascript html/script.js
// Listen for messages from Lua
window.addEventListener('message', function(event) {
    const data = event.data;
    if (data.type === 'open') {
        document.getElementById('app').style.display = 'block';
        document.getElementById('message').textContent = data.message;
    }
});

// Send data back to Lua
document.getElementById('closeBtn').addEventListener('click', function() {
    fetch('https://cfx-nui-' + GetParentResourceName() + '/closeNUI', {
        method: 'POST',
        headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
        body: JSON.stringify({ reason: 'button click' })
    });
    document.getElementById('app').style.display = 'none';
});
```

The `fetch` URL uses `GetParentResourceName()` — this is how NUI calls back to Lua.

### Step 5 - Handle NUI callbacks in Lua
_Goal: Lua receives the close signal and releases focus._

Add to `client.lua`:

```lua client.lua
-- Handle the close callback from NUI
RegisterNUICallback('closeNUI', function(data, cb)
    print(('NUI closed: %s'):format(data.reason))
    SetNuiFocus(false, false)  -- release keyboard and cursor
    cb('ok')  -- respond to the NUI callback
end)
```

Expected output:

```
Press E → overlay appears with "Hello from Lua!" → Click Close → overlay hides, F8 prints "NUI closed: button click".
```

## Common failures

| Exact error | Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| NUI shows but can't click | SetNuiFocus(false, true) — cursor true but keyboard false | Use SetNuiFocus(true, true) for interactive NUI |
| fetch to callback URL fails | Missing `files {}` entry for the JS file | List every file in fxmanifest `files {}` |
| NUI callback not firing | Callback name mismatch | The fetch URL path after resource name MUST match RegisterNUICallback name exactly |
| CSP blocks external fetch | Content Security Policy in next.config.ts | Add the external domain to the CSP |

The loading screen is the first thing players see. Five seconds of a branded, professional loading screen builds more trust than a hundred forum posts. This lesson builds one from scratch — logo, background, music, rotating tips — and explains every line.

### What this lesson covers
- You'll build: A branded loading screen with your server logo, background image, music track, and loading tips that display while players connect.
- Time: ~20 minutes
- You need: A local FiveM server, basic HTML/CSS knowledge, and an audio file (.ogg format).
- You'll learn: The loading screen architecture, HTML/CSS for the overlay, playing background music, cycling tips, and the correct fxmanifest setup.

### Before you start
- I have a local FiveM server.
- I know basic HTML and CSS.
- I have a logo image (PNG) and a short audio file (.ogg).

## Build it

### Step 1 - Create the resource
_Goal: The folder structure is ready._

```text
resources/my_loadingscreen/
  fxmanifest.lua
  index.html
  style.css
  script.js
  assets/
    logo.png
    background.jpg
    music.ogg
```

### Step 2 - Build the HTML page
_Goal: The loading screen displays your brand._

```html index.html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
    <div class="overlay">
        <img src="assets/logo.png" alt="Server Logo" class="logo">
        <h1>My FiveM Server</h1>
        <div class="loading-bar">
            <div class="progress" id="progressBar"></div>
        </div>
        <p id="tip">Loading amazing experiences...</p>
    </div>
    <audio id="bgMusic" loop>
        <source src="assets/music.ogg" type="audio/ogg">
    </audio>
    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

```css style.css
* { margin: 0; padding: 0; box-sizing: border-box; }
body {
    font-family: system-ui, sans-serif;
    background: url('assets/background.jpg') center/cover no-repeat;
    height: 100vh;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    color: white;
}
.overlay {
    background: rgba(0,0,0,0.7);
    padding: 48px;
    border-radius: 16px;
    text-align: center;
    max-width: 500px;
}
.logo { width: 120px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
h1 { font-size: 28px; margin-bottom: 24px; }
.loading-bar {
    background: rgba(255,255,255,0.2);
    border-radius: 4px;
    height: 6px;
    margin: 24px 0;
    overflow: hidden;
}
.progress {
    background: #0fb6c4;
    height: 100%;
    width: 0%;
    transition: width 0.3s;
}
#tip { font-size: 14px; opacity: 0.7; margin-top: 16px; }
```

```javascript script.js
// Rotating tips
const tips = [
    'Welcome to the best FiveM experience!',
    'Join our Discord: discord.gg/yourserver',
    'Need help? Type /help in chat.',
    'Check out our custom vehicles and jobs!',
];
let tipIndex = 0;
setInterval(() => {
    tipIndex = (tipIndex + 1) % tips.length;
    document.getElementById('tip').textContent = tips[tipIndex];
}, 4000);

// Start music
window.addEventListener('load', () => {
    document.getElementById('bgMusic').play().catch(() => {});
});

// Loading progress
let progress = 0;
const progressBar = document.getElementById('progressBar');
const interval = setInterval(() => {
    progress += Math.random() * 15;
    if (progress > 100) progress = 100;
    progressBar.style.width = progress + '%';
    if (progress >= 100) clearInterval(interval);
}, 300);
```

### Step 3 - Write fxmanifest and test
_Goal: The loading screen appears when players connect._

```lua fxmanifest.lua
fx_version 'cerulean'
game 'gta5'

loadscreen 'index.html'

files {
    'index.html',
    'style.css',
    'script.js',
    'assets/logo.png',
    'assets/background.jpg',
    'assets/music.ogg',
}
```

`loadscreen` is a dedicated manifest key — it tells FiveM to show this page during the loading phase and hide it automatically when the player spawns.

Ensure and reconnect. Your branded screen appears.

Expected output:

```
Reconnecting shows your logo, background, progress bar, rotating tips, and music.
```

## Common failures

| Exact error | Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Music doesn't play | Browser autoplay policy blocks audio | Add `play().catch(() => {})` — it silently ignores the autoplay block. Music plays after user interaction or on next load |
| Loading screen stays stuck | `loadscreen` script doesn't end naturally | FiveM hides the screen after all resources are loaded. If stuck, a resource is failing to start |
| Images don't appear | Path in HTML doesn't match `files {}` | Paths in HTML are relative to the resource root. Check `assets/logo.png` is listed in `files {}` |
| CSS doesn't apply | File not listed in `files {}` | Every file referenced in HTML must be listed in `files {}` |
